\begin_layout Title
Current State and Barriers to Global Adoption of Forensic Evaluative Reporting of Findings Given Activity-Level Propositions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
J Stacey,
 S Opperman,
 J Curran,
 SA Harbison
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
March 2025
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Abstract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper examines the current state and challenges in the global adoption of forensic evaluative reporting of findings given activity-level propositions.
 Forensic evaluative reporting provides a structured and objective assessment of findings that can be used in judicial proceedings.
 The assessment of findings given activity-level propositions addresses `how' and `when' questions about the presence of traces.
 This is often the question of interest to the fact-finder and practitioners are finding that they are faced with such questions on the stand with increasing frequency.
 However,
 despite its importance,
 widespread adoption has been hampered by several barriers.
 The paper explores the various concerns raised by the community in different jurisdictions,
 including reticence toward suggested methodologies,
 concern about lack of robust and impartial data to inform probabilities,
 regional differences in regulatory frameworks,
 and availability of training and resources to implement activity-level evaluations.
 Suggestions are made for overcoming these barriers and fostering greater global integration of activity-level evaluative reporting.
 By addressing these barriers,
 the paper aims to improve the credibility and utility of forensic evaluations in legal and investigative contexts around the world.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Forensic evaluative reporting is an ongoing area of development across many disciplines.
 The judicial system requires forensic practitioners to analyse traces of an event and assess the value of their results to help the fact-finder determine what may have occurred 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gill_dna_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This value is assigned in relation to the relevant information at hand and the question of importance for a case and often requires forensic knowledge to address.
 The results are only relevant to the context in which they are calculated,
 and if they are taken out of context,
 they can be meaningless and do not provide any added value 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "williams_embracing_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Determining the correct questions to address,
 in the form of propositions,
 is a key requirement of case interpretation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cook1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea of a hierarchy of propositions in case assessment and interpretation has been well-established within the forensic community and should not require introduction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cook1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The higher the type of proposition is in the hierarchy,
 the more relevant to the consideration carried out by the court 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gill_dna_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Forensic practitioners usually address findings given source or sub-source level propositions,
 such as whether the suspect is the source of the DNA profile found at a crime scene or whether fragments of glass found on a suspect are consistent with originating from a broken window.
 Many laboratories around the world are using probabilistic genotyping software to report findings on these types of questions,
 inherently using evaluative reporting by reporting likelihood ratios (LR).
 However,
 practices of reporting categorical statements are still a rampant problem,
 suggesting limited uptake of recommendations published in recent years 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bali_communicating_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This has meant the expansion of evaluative reporting to forensic traces given activity level propositions remains an emerging topic many years after a framework was posited to address this type of issue 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Evett2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These evaluations may be helpful when the actor,
 mechanism or timing of the activity is at question 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "taylor_forensic_2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this paper we shall refer to these as activity-level evaluations but at no point do we mean that the evaluation is of the propositions themselves,
 rather the assessment of finding such traces given an activity proposition has occurred.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The need for the assessment of activity-level evaluations is a growing area of concern.
 Jackson and Biedermann (2019) reported that experts regularly give testimony the occurrence of an activity premise that could result in DNA being present 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jackson2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Yang et al (2022) asked American forensic experts about their court experiences of the prior three years.
 Only ten of the fifty respondents had not been asked to testify on DNA transfer,
 and more than half of respondents (59%) had been asked to discuss activities that may have deposited the traces that were found 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Yangetal2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Prinz et al carried out a larger follow-on survey of practitioners in 2024 to understand the global forensic community's experience and opinion on activity-level evaluations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Prinzetal2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Fifty-one percent of 152 respondents had been asked to testify to activity-level propositions in the prior 3 years 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Prinzetal2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This grows to 59% when reframed as discussing finding a DNA result under consideration of possible activities,
 and almost 68% of 155 respondents were asked to testify on DNA transfer in the same period 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Prinzetal2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A majority of respondents to Yang's survey of American practitioners also indicated that formal activity-level evaluation of findings would be helpful (36/ 53 respondents) or would be helpful to a jury (38/53 respondents) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Yangetal2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most published works on the evaluation of activity-level propositions are in the discipline of forensic biology.
 This is understandable when considering the complexity of DNA interpretation when compared to other evidence types.
 Often,
 practitioners presenting DNA traces to courts find that questions posed during judicial processes agree on the contributor of the DNA in question but not the circumstances that occurred to cause its presence.
 Although other disciplines are increasingly finding similar questions posed,
 forensic biology practitioners have reported that such questioning frequently occurs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Yangetal2022,Prinzetal2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is not to say that other disciplines are not investigating evaluative reporting given activity scenarios.
 Studies in glass 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "curran_estimating_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 fingerprints 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "de_ronde_evaluation_2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 fibres 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "taroni_generalised_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 handwriting 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bird_formulation_2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and drugs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "russell_establishing_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 are all easily found in the literature in conjunction with activity-level proposition evaluation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bayesian Networks (BNs) are often used as a tool for forensic evaluative reporting.
 The first use of BNs in a forensic context was purported to be in 1989 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "aitken_probabilistic_1989"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 (as reported by Dawid and Evett in 1997 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "philip_dawid_using_1997"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 With the ethical concerns of transparency and explainability in algorithms becoming a topical issue,
 the use of a visual method for the representation of the calculations that are caried out seems to be an intuitive approach to help alleviate this concern.
 BNs have been suggested as such an approach 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Derks2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Yet,
 there seems to be a global difference of opinion in the need for conducting evaluative reporting given a higher proposition level or the use of BNs for the process.
 Some laboratories around the world have implemented networks for the assessment of findings given activity-level propositions,
 such as at the Netherlands Forensic Institute for forensic biology cases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kokshoorn_reporting_2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Others,
 such as the University Center of Legal Medicine,
 Lausanne,
 Switzerland,
 have implemented BNs for the attribution of biological source for traces that have been recovered 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Samie2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Still,
 many laboratories are not yet comfortable with evaluating activity-level propositions at all,
 and others prefer not to use Bayesian Networks as an evaluation tool.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assessment of activity-level evaluations appears to have stalled.
 Since the excellent reviews by Taylor et al in 2018 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TaylorKokshoornBiedermann2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Schaapveld et al in 2019 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Schaapveld2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 there has been little change is the global position on evaluative reporting and the use of BNs.
 Further discussion has instead pivoted to address identified gaps.
 Recent literature has focussed on examples of the use of Bayesian Networks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "taroni_generalised_2021,MarchTaroni2020,Uitdehaag2022,osnat_likelihood-ratio_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or experiments to grow knowledge in transfer,
 prevalence,
 persistence and recovery (TPPR) of traces in many disciplines 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "curran_estimating_2024,de_ronde_evaluation_2019,russell_establishing_2021,davidson_transfer_2024,falardeau_distribution_2020,lim-hitchings_frequented_2024,sijen_identification_2021,szkuta_dna_2020,taylor_accounting_2024,taylor_importance_2021,vergeer_evaluation_2020,voigt_re-imagen_2024,zacher_transfer_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In contrast,
 much of the opposing opinion on higher-level evaluations resides in social media or review journals that do not offer the ability of rebuttal,
 rather than in peer-reviewed journal publications where free and frank discussion can be held.
 This makes addressing the concerns difficult,
 as conversation participants are limited to those few who are comfortable opining publicly on either side of the disagreement.
 In many ways,
 the highlighted issues with activity-level evaluations arise from the concerns with probabilistic frameworks in general.
 This paper will identify and collate the barriers standing in the way of global acceptance of forensic activity-level evaluations and open a discussion of what is required to find a unified way forward.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Current Barriers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Duty of a Forensic Expert?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While globally,
 forensic practitioners agree that the assessment of findings given offense-level propositions are the remit of the fact-finder to decide,
 the question of who should address activity-level propositions is in contention.
 Over half (56%) of global forensic practitioners surveyed held the opinion is that it is the role of the forensic expert witness to speak to possible activities that result in the detection of DNA traces
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Defined by the authors as traces with no obvious attributable body fluid source.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Prinzetal2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This indicates that there is a substantial minority who feel otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some practitioners have held the opinion that activity-level evaluations are the province of the forensic practitioner for some time 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "champod_dna_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Vuille and Taroni (2021) state that uncertainty is inherent to the forensic process and,
 with the increasingly small limits of detection offered by newest methods,
 focussing on analytical results alone runs the risk of blinding the court to the probative value of the recovered traces within the context of the case 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vuille_measuring_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 There is a danger if the fact-finder is left to interpret weight of evidence statements without the benefit of forensic training.
 If not properly explained,
 a mismatch between evaluations at sub-source level and activity level can occur,
 potentially leading to inappropriate conclusions as strengths of evidence are misapplied 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "biedermann_importance_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The European Network of Forensic Science Institutes (ENFSI) released guidelines in 2016 that state that forensic practitioners have a duty to help the court by explaining the significance of their findings 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "european_network_of_forensic_science_institutes_enfsi_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Further,
 they recommend that practitioners assess activity-level propositions whenever understanding the scientific findings would require domain knowledge or information that the fact-finder would not possess,
 especially if there is a possibility that the courts would be misled if findings are presented without the context of alleged activities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "european_network_of_forensic_science_institutes_enfsi_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The United Kingdom Forensic Regulator (UKFR) state that 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

even where data are limited,
 it is by far preferable to use a logically correct approach,
 being transparent about any limitations arising from a paucity of data,
 rather than to persist with unstructured and often unscientific approaches
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "uk_forensic_science_regulator_codes_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The DNA commission of the International Society for Forensic Genetics (ISFG) agree that although 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

giving a direct opinion on propositions is beyond the scope of the scientist
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and may fall very close to offense-level propositions,
 addressing the findings given an activity proposition is within their remit 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gill_dna_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Crispino et al (2021) opined that an expert witness has a duty to express an opinion on the observations and results within their area of expertise 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Crispinoetal2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The boundaries of this area of expertise for a forensic practitioner appear to be unclear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Netherlands Register for Court Experts (NRGD) have a set of standards for DNA analysis and interpretation that includes activity level analysis as a sub-field for a registered forensic expert in the area of Human DNA Analysis and Interpretation (added in September 2020) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NRGDStandard-2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Whereas,
 the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) working group on Human Factors in DNA Interpretation consider the assessment of traces given activity-level propositions to be a distinct skill separate from standard DNA interpretation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nist_expert_working_group_on_human_factors_in_forensic_dna_interpretation_forensic_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The group recommends that evaluations given activity-level propositions should only be carried out by properly trained and competent analysts with knowledge of DNA TPPR characteristics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nist_expert_working_group_on_human_factors_in_forensic_dna_interpretation_forensic_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although this discussion has occurred only in relation to the interpretation of DNA evidence,
 it is expected that such feelings would be similar across other disciplines.
 A common approach to the remit of a forensic practitioner needs to be attained to provide clarity and guidance to the justice sector of different jurisdictions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "miranda_is_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Understanding and Describing Error
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A forensic practitioner must feel comfortable working with uncertainty,
 as they are asked to give an opinion about events of the past from only minute traces that have been left by the actions that have occurred.
 This is even more the case when addressing activity-level evaluations,
 as activity-level evaluations almost always involve more uncertainty than lower levels in the hierarchy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "butler_dna_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Martire et al described forensic error in their 2024 study as being subjective,
 multidimensional,
 unavoidable,
 cultural,
 educational,
 misunderstood and transdisciplinary 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "martire_understanding_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Understanding and communicating the sources of this uncertainty supports the scientific validity of obtained findings.
 This is a key underlying requirement of forensic practice to enable trust 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "presidents_council_of_advisors_on_science_and_technology_pcast_report_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Legal standards used in many countries for expert witness testimony admissibility also include a requirement to clearly communicate the uncertainty of all methodology that has been used 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "blackmun_daubert_1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Stating findings without disclosing a method's error rate is equivalent of suggesting an error rate of zero 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "leonetti_ensuring_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is an impossible achievement for any finding and suggesting such is misleading to the fact-finder 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "presidents_council_of_advisors_on_science_and_technology_pcast_report_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Australia New Zealand Policing Advisory Agency - National Institutes of Forensic Science (ANZPAA-NIFS) released a report in 2017 introducing evaluative reporting as a response to concerns raised by the United States President's Council of Advisors on Science and Technology (PCAST) that uncertainty was not explicitly considered in comparative forensic evaluations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "presidents_council_of_advisors_on_science_and_technology_pcast_report_2016,ballantyne_introductory_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Even so,
 there is still a concern within the community that activity-level evaluations do not do enough to explicitly include uncertainty.
 Practitioners focus on the inclusion of uncertainty in three areas:
 what propositions are assessed,
 error in the underlying measurements used as prior knowledge,
 and description of error in the resulting likelihood ratio that is calculated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection

\emph on
Propositions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The choice of propositions that are evaluated is important.
 It decides the scope of the assessment and gives relevance to the resulting likelihood ratio that is obtained.
 It is recommended that propositions for activity-level evaluation are statements about activities rather than including findings or transfer mechanisms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gill_dna_2020,european_network_of_forensic_science_institutes_enfsi_2016,organization_of_scientific_area_committees_osac_for_forensic_science_best_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 One issue is ensuring that the analyst has the correct training in how to define appropriate propositions to achieve meaningful,
 transparent,
 and correct logical deductions.
 Hicks et al (2015) showed that the propositions that are set have a large impact on the values that are obtained 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hicks_importance_2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Taylor et al (2018) also attempted to give guidance on how to formulate propositions appropriate for each proposition level 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TaylorKokshoornBiedermann2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the underlying assumptions of Bayesian inference is that the propositions that are assessed are mutually exclusive and cover all possibilities (are exhaustive).
 Whilst ideal,
 determining an exhaustive list of propositions is difficult in forensic casework to the point of impracticability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "buckleton_when_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The list of possible activity scenarios giving rise to found traces is potentially unlimited,
 with some scenarios more plausible than others 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vlek2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Possible mechanisms extend vastly wider than just considering a prosecution point of view versus an alternate point of view.
 In many jurisdictions,
 forensic analyses are split into siloed disciplines,
 making it challenging to access case information needed to formulate propositions to assess activity-related factors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "biedermann_importance_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally,
 there is no requirement in many jurisdictions for defense counsel to provide an alternate proposition,
 it is up to the practitioner to determine what that alternate proposition should be based on their own knowledge of the case.
 In some jurisdictions,
 the defense strategy can also be dynamic,
 so evaluations that have been decided pre-trial may be insufficient to deal with scenarios that are presented or shifts in defense strategies that may occur during a trial 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "texas_forensic_science_comission_final_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore,
 constraints such as limited case information and resources to examine items can affect the setting of propositions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tayloretal2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This concerns practitioners,
 who consider that slight changes in known circumstances might distort the magnitude and direction of the reported evidentiary support presented to the fact-finder.
 If the analyst is well-trained,
 it might be possible to rebut such changes in scenario if the witness understands how the TPPR mechanisms that are posited relate to those used in the activity-level evaluation.
 Although a provided scenario may be less likely than the calculated proposition or further calculation may be required,
 this does not mean that activity-level evaluations should be entirely avoided.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several published guideline documents do not require evaluated propositions to be exhaustive 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gill_dna_2020,european_network_of_forensic_science_institutes_enfsi_2016,nist_expert_working_group_on_human_factors_in_forensic_dna_interpretation_forensic_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This approach has been taken as all evaluations are conducted within the context of assumptions and the information known about the case.
 All calculated likelihood values are within this context.
 If the context and limitations of the analysis are clearly communicated,
 the propositions can be considered as effectively exhaustive within that context.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vlek et al (2015) suggested a different approach,
 where BNs are created with different scenarios as sub-graphs.
 The sub-graphs are controlled with constraint nodes to ensure inconsistent or mutually exclusive events are impossible 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vlek2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The authors took an approach based on Shannon's Information Theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rioul_this_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 in that an implausible event gives more evidentiary support than occurrence of a common event 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vlek2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection

\emph on
Insufficiency of Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
T.o perform activity-level evaluations,
 the practitioner needs to understand how much of the trace would be expected to be present and able to be recovered in innocent circumstances.
 Many practitioners are concerned that there is a lack of data on which to base likelihood values in relation to activities.
 They feel that the mechanisms of TPPR,
 especially in relation to DNA,
 are much too variable to allow accurate assessment of findings in relation to probable activity.
 There is concern that this variation means that there is insufficient published data to allow an analysis to be supported 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Taylor2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The rate at which different people shed DNA,
 variation in TPPR characteristics and extenuating circumstances,
 such as cohabitation,
 could cause unreliable determination of likelihood values in an activity-level evaluation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "champod_dna_2013,butler_dna_2024,vanOorschot2019"
