\begin_layout Standard
The way in which findings given activity propositions are addressed is undergoing considerable change.
 Historically,
 in some jurisdictions,
 the expert witness has been able to address activity scenarios as opinion evidence.
 Forensic practitioners may have many years of experience working in their discipline,
 calibrated through continuing education,
 validation work with a ground-truth that is known or case-specific experiments and have an intrinsic understanding of how findings change in different case circumstances.
 There are differences of opinion whether determining an understanding of likelihood on such experience alone is sufficiently robust 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "champod_dna_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Published guidelines are not in agreement about whether an opinion should be determined using experience alone,
 or if a balanced evaluation should be carried out using a combination of data sources 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "organization_of_scientific_area_committees_osac_for_forensic_science_best_2022,european_network_of_forensic_science_institutes_enfsi_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The Organization of Scientific Area Committees (OSAC) for Forensic Science are not stringent in their requirements,
 recommending activity-level evaluative reporting ranging from qualitative analysis based on practitioner knowledge alone to full Bayesian Network derived likelihood ratios fully supported by published studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "organization_of_scientific_area_committees_osac_for_forensic_science_best_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 ANZPAA-NIFS state that the body of knowledge used during evaluation could 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

include published literature,
 databases of characteristic frequencies,
 knowledge of analysis limitations,
 professional experience 
\emph on
or
\emph default
 personal knowledge,
 beliefs and assumptions.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ballantyne_introductory_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Emphasis added.
 ENFSI and IFSG guidelines set out that a variety of data sources should be used 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gill_dna_2020,european_network_of_forensic_science_institutes_enfsi_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Until agreement is obtained,
 approaches taken are likely to be left to discussion within different jurisdictions or the judicial proceedings of a specific case due to the complexity of case circumstances.
 Conversely,
 the guidelines also recognise that published data may insufficiently resemble the case at hand and allow that empirical research or personal opinion may be needed to address the gap.
 All state that the demarcation between data-based and opinion-based inputs must be made clear to the fact-finder.
 Why certain studies were used and on what information all prior probability values have been based should be documented to ensure transparency in the analytical process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experiments in TPPR have long been a feature in publications as practitioners try to understand this vast and dynamic area of uncertainty.
 There has been criticism in the past that many studies are not well-designed or try to describe unrealistic scenarios.
 In addition,
 the diverse laboratory methods used to elicit DNA results complicate comparison of data.
 These statements may apply but this does not detract from an overall understanding of the factors involved in TPPR.
 Van Oorschot et al (2019) published a report on prevailing factors in DNA TPPR 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vanOorschot2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A follow up review of DNA TPPR from various body areas has also recently been published 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "woollacott_transfer_2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Butler (2024) has also presented a review of DNA TPPR factors from the literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "butler_dna_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Of late,
 focus has pivoted to looking at TPPR with more of an activity-level lens to support the execution of these types of evaluations.
 For example,
 in relation to DNA,
 recent studies have attempted to clarify shedding status 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ali_how_2024,taylor_using_2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Gill et al (2021) have also published a framework to address DNA transfer scenarios on skin to inform activity-level evaluations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gill2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 ENFSI agencies have jointly attempted to characterise the variation that is introduced into DNA results by the analysis process to support creation of Bayesian networks for activity-level evaluation that are reproducible across different laboratories 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gill_react_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An additional consideration is that any contamination of traces after the crime would be unable to be distinguished from relevant or preexisting amounts.
 As traces easily transfer,
 it is necessary to understand and minimise contamination mechanisms throughout the analytical process,
 from the crime scene onward 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "butler_dna_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Multiple TPPR studies have covered this topic,
 ranging from case studies where contamination has occurred 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pickrahn_contamination_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to assessments of packaging and instrumentation that has been used 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "taylor_accounting_2024,szkuta_dna_2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Management techniques such as DNA elimination databases that include all people involved in sample collection and processing have been advocated by many groups for activity-level evaluations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gill_dna_2020,taylor_forensic_2023,butler_dna_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is also no guidance as to how much data is required for an evaluation to be deemed robust 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "texas_forensic_science_comission_final_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Evaluations are often conducted using measured data as a prior understanding of likelihood.
 Practitioners have concerns that if probabilities for a method or event are based on experimental results,
 how certain are the results to be representative of the full variation of real casework results that might be obtained.
 Given the number of published studies that have insufficient sample sizes to be considered robust,
 how can robust statistical evaluation be conducted?
 Concerns have been raised that having insufficient prior knowledge for a BN would lead to a lack of robustness in the results that are obtained.
 Taylor et al (2016) pointed out that Bayesian inference depends on the observed data more than prior knowledge 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Taylor2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A balanced assignment of 0.5 or equal probability over all possibilities inherently indicates when no prior knowledge is known.
 Intrinsically,
 this is a fair way to include mechanisms where there is less reported data.
 The authors suggested using sensitivity testing for assessing the uncertainty that is introduced by gaps in prior knowledge on a final calculated likelihood ratio 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Taylor2016,taylor_practical_2024,Gill2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The use of qualitative Bayesian networks has also been proposed to assess the effect of data quality and availability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BiedermannTaroni2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The NIST Human Factors working group recognised that some cases may allow the evaluation of finding given a set of specific scenarios but that this evaluation must follow DNA interpretation best practice 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nist_expert_working_group_on_human_factors_in_forensic_dna_interpretation_forensic_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Specifically,
 addressing the likelihood of finding the recovered traces under the condition of two opposing propositions within the framework of circumstances for the case and avoiding the fallacy of transposing the conditional by addressing a single proposition directly 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hicks_logical_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bayesian statistics incorporates uncertainty by using prior knowledge and data to show support for a process or activity in the form of a probability distribution.
 It will always be based on the practitioner's knowledge and experience 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "taroni_reconciliation_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The key point to strive for in addressing uncertainty in evaluation outcomes is the attempt to standardise that prior knowledge through sharing and documentation of the prior data that has been used.
 There are also improvements that could be made to the algorithms that are used in BNs.
 One area where they could be improved is in the representation of data.
 Current implementations or software options for creating BNs only allow probability nodes to be either discrete probabilities or continuous probability densities distributed with a Gaussian (Normal) distribution only.
 This is unrealistic for many situations where continuous functions of a different type might be more appropriate.
\end_layout

