Creditable interval for likelihood ratio
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When using a Bayesian framework,
 each evaluation that is conducted will result in different likelihood ratio (LR) values being obtained by different analysts.
 This concerns forensic practitioners who desire reproducible outcomes to ensure accurate results are reported to the judiciary.
 There is a feeling that variation in values that are obtained from different practitioners indicates that the methodology does not meet the specifications set out by the President's Council of Advisors on Science and Technology (PCAST) in their 2016 report on the validity of forensic methods,
 to be 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

repeatable,
 reproducible,
 and accurate
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "presidents_council_of_advisors_on_science_and_technology_pcast_report_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Practitioners consider that this stipulation requires the reporting of an interval to indicate the uncertainty of the likelihood ratio metric.
 Discussions of this type have been carried out about the statistics at a sub-source level and are ongoing in the literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dror_most_2023,buckleton_extending_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 At an activity level,
 this is not as large a concern as evaluations do not include Monte Carlo sampling methods that are a source of variation in the values that are obtained.
 Taroni et al (2016) argued that the idea of setting a creditable interval on a likelihood ratio is a misunderstanding of Bayesian principles 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "taroni_dismissal_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The likelihood ratio value is a ratio between two single values that have been obtained though intermediate decision points where the use of decided parameters and posterior mean probabilities are used to inform the final belief in likelihood for both propositions.
 Uncertainty in the LR value is merely a downstream effect of the uncertainty of the preceding decisions.
 If those decisions are justified and documented there is no call to propagate the uncertainty to the value presented to the fact-finder.
 Doing so is unnecessarily confusing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "taroni_dismissal_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 There is no true value for the metric 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "butler_dna_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
 a measure of uncertainty is meaningless within the context of a specific case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Contextual Bias and Subjectivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Subjectivity is considered by many to be a problem to be avoided within forensic practice with multiple recommendations over the years stipulating that forensic science must strive for the attainment of only objective analysis and interpretation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "buckleton_extending_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Influencing of the outcome of analyses by human perception,
 or the personal beliefs and knowledge of the analyst,
 has the potential to lead to miscarriages of justice 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "budowle_perspective_2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Yet,
 subjectivity is not always negative 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "budowle_perspective_2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In fact,
 like uncertainty,
 subjectivity is inherent in human nature and is unavoidable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "winburn_objectivity_2021,winburn_response_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It can merely be minimised using management techniques.
 Some sociologists even feel that observation in the absence of subjective perspective is both impossible and a distortion of reality 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "boon_subjectivity_2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It also should not be confused with subject matter expertise which is a collective state based on experience and knowledge of an area rather than personal beliefs or feelings.
 The addition of subject matter expertise can enrich an analysis.
 Dror (2020) described biases that could lead to subjectivity as coming from eight different sources 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dror_cognitive_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These sources may affect various aspects of the analytical process differently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contextual bias,
 caused by having knowledge of task-irrelevant information is a major influencer of subjectivity.
 To avoid it,
 it is recommended that forensic service providers implement context management practices for comparative disciplines 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dror_contextual_2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The Royal Statistical Society recommends separation of sample analysis and comparisons from case management to reduce the potential analysis outcomes being affected by unconscious bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rss_statistics_and_the_law_section_healthcare_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The interpretation of analytical results should be separated from further contextual knowledge of the case 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dror_subjectivity_2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Other practices include analysing evidential samples separately prior to comparison with a provided reference sample to ensure that features arising from noise or below analytical thresholds are not given extra weight by knowing that the reference contains a similar feature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some contextual bias is inevitable as time and cost restraints mean that triaging the type of testing to be performed is required.
 It is the practitioner's responsibility to understand where there is a risk of bias and minimise it wherever possible.
 The implementation of standard operating procedures or analytical thresholds can mitigate but not eliminate bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dror_most_2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For example,
 genomic analysis uses a quality metric in base calling of a sample to indicate the uncertainty of the base that is called being true.
 This allows a method of interpreting the observation when it is compared and may determine if some areas of DNA are excluded from the overall comparison.
 Including a quality metric in image comparison could enable noisy or distorted parts of an image to be excluded from match criteria.
 The number of contributors in a DNA mixture,
 or whether minor contributors are included or excluded,
 may change depending on the rules of peak interpretation that are used in evidential sample analysis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "buckleton_extending_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the need for context management practices to reduce the influence of irrelevant information on the outcome of analytical techniques exists,
 the term 'task-relevant information' should be kept in mind.
 Contextual information is not by nature biasing.
 It is only its relevance to the task at hand that decides this.
 A forensic practitioner who is asked to assess activity-level propositions needs to be aware of any information that will change the probability of the propositions that they are assessing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gill_dna_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Using published data to add value by reducing uncertainty is useful if it can be added in a measurable and standardised way.
 Interpretation of individual samples is negatively affected by contextual information,
 so bias is increased.
 But activity-level interpretation,
 and sometimes source attribution,
 requires that information that is biasing at lower-level proposition considerations.
 Knowing the result of multiple tests or background information is needed to answer the question making the information that was previously considered task-irrelevant now relevant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The contextual information that is needed means that careful consideration should be conducted as to the appropriate role to perform activity-level proposition evaluations.
 The assessment of activity-level propositions is at higher level requiring knowledge in excess to that given to bench analysts
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gill_dna_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In some organisations,
 case managers are assigned who use features of a case to determine the most efficient and value-adding methods of analysis to use.
 This information is similar to that required for activity-level evaluation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All guidelines recommend that the Case Assessment and Interpretation (CAI) model published by Cook et al (1998) is followed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cook1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Specifically,
 that the evaluation framework is decided upon by the practitioner prior to any analytical results being obtained.
 This pre-assessment also guides what nodes should be included in a Bayesian network.
 The more nodes,
 the more computationally expensive it is to carry out inference 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChenPollino2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It is also recommended that the decision of what propositions to evaluate is carried out during pre-assessment to avoid contextual bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "european_network_of_forensic_science_institutes_enfsi_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Changes should not be made to the assessed propositions after observing results,
 unless driven by new case information (38).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the use of machine learning (ML) and artificial intelligence (AI) tools rises,
 bias must be kept at the forefront of mind.
 Algorithms do not reduce bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dror_cognitive_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The use of achine learning (ML) or artificial intelligence (AI) tools for comparison has made this a topical issue as samples provided to AI for comparison will not distinguish between the origins of features,
 merely how similar features in two observations are to each other.
 Models are trained with a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

ground truth
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 which is a human-decided concept introducing another source of uncertainty.
 Sample collection methodology or instrumentation can also influence a match decision.
 For example,
 consider the effect of colour-blindness or camera sensor variation on the perception of a presumptive test colour result 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "marques-mateu_quantifying_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Algorithms are made by people and will incorporate the biases of their creators.
 AI models for classification also provide a match probability as they do not consider the likelihood of the findings given that an alternative source was the origin.
 As people become more familiar with using such tools,
 there is a risk of confirmation bias occurring where the practitioner accepts the given answer without assessment of its validity.
 The role of AI systems in forensics is to provide curated knowledge and insights to support the practitioner in defining their expert opinion,
 not to replace the expert or give a cookie-cutter response that is passed onto the courts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Understanding the underlying frequency of an event is required to compare like with like.
 This is called base rate knowledge and can be a source of bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dror_cognitive_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is aligns with Shannon's information theory,
 where rare information is more informative than common 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rioul_this_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Things that commonly occur add little information to determine if an event of interest has occurred.
 Situations such as medical malpractice cases where an understanding of the base rate of time in ward and death rate is required 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rss_statistics_and_the_law_section_healthcare_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Events that seem rare can occur by coincidence or in clusters 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rss_statistics_and_the_law_section_healthcare_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 That is,
 if the rare piece of information is observed at all,
 which is a known problem in visual searches 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wolfe_low_2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Careful interpretation is needed,
 as high base rates can bias conclusions if low probability of an alternative state is disregarded in conclusions.
 For example,
 if 90% of strangulation cases are homicide and the rest are self-inflicted,
 the underlying base rate of homicides compared to that of suicide needs to be considered when calculating a likelihood ratio.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Training of Experts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Specific training for conducting activity-level reporting is advised by international guidelines.
 The NIST working group recommended that forensic experts should avoid giving testimony on how or when DNA might have been deposited until they are appropriately trained in how to respond to such questions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nist_expert_working_group_on_human_factors_in_forensic_dna_interpretation_forensic_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
