\begin_layout Standard
In principle,
 the statistics used with activity-level proposition evaluation are the same as methods used at lower levels of the hierarchy.
 That being the case,
 there are many practitioners with extensive experience and understanding of the techniques.
 There are also long-serving practitioners who have gained an intrinsic understanding of TPPR mechanisms through their casework experience which shapes their opinion.
 However,
 the verification of the expertise of a practitioner should be supported by documentation to justify the claim.
 Standardised training would ensure that the issues practitioners must also be aware of when conducting activity-level evaluations are all covered.
 Additionally,
 there is a need for an awareness of bias as it relates to evaluation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Options for the training of forensic practitioners in activity-level evaluative reporting are few,
 such as those provided by the University of Lausanne 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "noauthor_statistics_2023,noauthor_advanced_2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Courses range from ~7 hour awareness training workshops at conferences 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kalafut_beyond_2024,kalafut_longest_2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to full 21 month continuing education courses 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "noauthor_statistics_2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These courses cover aspects of case assessment and interpretation,
 how to set appropriate propositions,
 awareness of the need to understand the background knowledge relevant to the case circumstances,
 understand when data from studies should or should not be included and training in how to present such evidence to the fact-finder.
 The core activities stipulated in the NRDG code of conduct also include these topics.
 This shows that training is much more widespread than an understanding of Bayesian statistics and network structure.
\end_layout

