\begin_layout Subsection
Guidelines and Standards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 2023 book by Taylor and Kokshoorn remains one of the most referenced works in the field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "taylor_forensic_2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In addition,
 there are now many guidelines in existence that support evaluative reporting practices.
 Internationally,
 several consortiums and organisations have published guidance to inform how to conduct forensic evaluative reporting at various levels of the hierarchy of propositions.
 ENSFI released their guidelines in 2016 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "european_network_of_forensic_science_institutes_enfsi_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 They set out an understanding that a forensic practitioner should carry out activity-level evaluations with an eye to balance (using mutually exclusive propositions),
 logic (addressing findings given propositions),
 robustness (inferences are based on sound knowledge and can withstand scrutiny) and transparency (process to reach conclusion is evident).
 These values have combined with the Cook et al case assessment and interpretation (CAI) framework 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cook1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to form the backbone on which later guidelines and standards have been built.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2017,
 a multi-organisation working group for ANZPAA-NIFS released an introductory guidance document on evaluative reporting in general,
 but included consideration that activity-level evaluations may be appropriate 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ballantyne_introductory_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This covered the basic framework and process including proposition setting,
 likelihood calculation and scales and considerations in transitioning from traditional reporting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The DNA Commission of the ISFG published their own guidelines in 2020 for the evaluation of biological traces considering activity level propositions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gill_dna_2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 They made eleven recommendations covering the use of likelihood ratios;
 addressing concise,
 simple,
 mutually exclusive propositions;
 addressing issues at an explicitly specified level within the hierarchy of propositions;
 not speaking to methods of transfer or propositions directly;
 and ensuring results are not included in the content of the propositions.
 They stated that evaluation should be carried out in terms of DNA recovery,
 as it inherently includes consideration of transfer,
 persistence and recovery,
 and a verbal scale of likelihood is optional but cannot be used by itself.
 These recommendations are comprehensive and are looked to by many jurisdictions as sufficient.
 Nevertheless,
 other jurisdictions still feel that additional guidance is needed that reflects their specific judicial requirements 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "texas_forensic_science_comission_final_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This runs the risk that guidance diverges globally leading to inconsistent outcomes depending on jurisdiction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "buckleton_extending_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The NRGD standards were updated in 2020 to set out the expectations of the skills,
 knowledge and expected tasks which the analyst requires for activity level interpretation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NRGDStandard-2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However,
 they do not offer guidance on best practice.
 The UKFR released an appendix to their Code of Conduct covering the development of evaluative opinion including at the activity-level in 2021 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "uk_forensic_science_regulator_codes_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 They took the opposite approach and included more guidance than would normally be found in standards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
OSAC drafted best practice guidelines for evaluative reporting of forensic biology findings given propositions of activity-level and below in 2022 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "organization_of_scientific_area_committees_osac_for_forensic_science_best_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 OSAC guidelines also recommend that possibilities should not be testified to by a forensic expert.
 They offer no clarity to the fact-finder as to the strength of support as possibilities can range from exceedingly unlikely to occur to near certainty 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "organization_of_scientific_area_committees_osac_for_forensic_science_best_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For all proposition levels,
 they distinguish probabilities explicitly calculated from a model from 
\emph on
notional
\emph default
 probabilities derived from published data,
 internal experiments or analyst's experience 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "organization_of_scientific_area_committees_osac_for_forensic_science_best_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 ENFSI guidelines also discuss 
\emph on
subjective
\emph default
 probabilities as a separate subclass of probability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "european_network_of_forensic_science_institutes_enfsi_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Emphasis added.
 This conflicts with the opinion of others,
 who consider all probabilities to be personal/notional whether or not they are based on experience or empirical evidence 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "taroni_reconciliation_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
NIST released two reports in 2024 relating to DNA interpretation.
 The first made forty-four recommendations to address human factors in forensic DNA casework 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nist_expert_working_group_on_human_factors_in_forensic_dna_interpretation_forensic_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Many of these relate directly or indirectly to activity-level evaluations.
 The recommendations fall into broad categories:
 applying best practice for interpretation and documentation;
 assessment and mitigation of bias and error;
 development of policies and practices for addressing activity-level questions;
 considerations for DNA analysis settings and interpretation methods;
 format of reported likelihood ratios;
 other reporting language and content;
 advice on testimony content;
 promoting collaboration,
 communication and training;
 creating robust quality assurance systems;
 encouraging engaged and defined leadership;
 and creating a productive,
 research and innovation driven workplace environment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
NIST's mixture interpretation Scientific Foundation Review published in 2024 contains a chapter covering DNA interpretation at the activity level 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "butler_dna_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The author faced a similar problem to that faced by practitioners in trying to find relevant data to use for evaluations requiring multiple searches of public abstract databases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "butler_dna_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Many of the recommendations are aligned with previous guidelines.
 The author acknowledged that a match between a reference and an evidentiary sample does not automatically indicate that the person participated in the crime due to DNA transfer characteristics.
 The author recommended that low level,
 poor quality or only a partial DNA traces,
 or cases where there is a reasonable expectation for the prior presence of the trace,
 should be evaluated at the activity level 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "butler_dna_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The review also recommended that if reporting of a likelihood ratio at a sub-source level would be irrelevant and likely to mislead then it should not be reported.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wording used in current guidelines is confusing when recommending how activity-level evaluations should be reported.
 In contrast,
 ISFG guidelines explicitly state that verbal scales should not be used alone,
 ENFSI,
 ANZPAA-NIFS and OSAC are more ambiguous 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gill_dna_2020,european_network_of_forensic_science_institutes_enfsi_2016,organization_of_scientific_area_committees_osac_for_forensic_science_best_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 ENFSI and OSAC state that numeric likelihood ratios 
\emph on
and/or
\emph default
 verbal scales should be reported 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "european_network_of_forensic_science_institutes_enfsi_2016,organization_of_scientific_area_committees_osac_for_forensic_science_best_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Emphasis added.
 ANZPAA-NIFS allows that non-numerical likelihoods might be reported 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ballantyne_introductory_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This has created a lack of clarity in some jurisdictions as to whether a verbal scale alone should be acceptable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "texas_forensic_science_comission_final_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A noticeable gap in international guidelines is how activity-level evaluations should be conducted by experts called as a rebuttal witness,
 as is allowed in the United States.
 Rebuttal witnesses often are not given sufficient time to prepare a full statement 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "texas_forensic_science_comission_final_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The requirement that all evaluations be reported in a peer-reviewed written statement runs the risk that the expert opinion of someone trained in activity-level evaluations is unable to help clarify testimony.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While guidelines have been published,
 there also remains the lack of an accreditation framework or standards for the basis of a quality assurance system for activity-level evaluations.
 Many practitioners do not want to implement activity-level evaluations for their casework until these are released.
 However,
 until recently,
 it has been acceptable for practitioners to provide testimony on these considerations without any sort of quality checks at all.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A way forward
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Grow and collate global TPPR knowledge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The recognition that TPPR knowledge is required to allow the assessment of findings given activity-level propositions has been acknowledged and has in recent years led to an increase in publication of TPPR experiments.
 Many explicitly stating they are performed to inform activity proposition evaluation.
 Most of these are to describe TPPR of biological traces with other disciplines not currently yet publishing studies.
 This will be an ongoing process as the wide range of possible and plausible activities is dynamic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recognition that the study design of past studies has complicated systematic comparisons has led to the recommendation that guidelines and strategies are implemented to improve the design and carry out systematic reviews of published research 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gosch_dna_2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The introduction of comprehensive and searchable DNA transfer database has also been advocated by many groups 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gill_dna_2020,taylor_forensic_2023,texas_forensic_science_comission_final_2024,vanOorschot2019,gosch_dna_2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The discrepancy of knowledge between different experts makes it extremely difficult to gain consensus across the forensic community.
 This may lead to disagreements between experts in the courtroom,
 complicating the decision to be made by the fact-finder.
 Collation of published TPPR data into a centralised storage system has been attempted.
 Kokshoorn et al (2018) have attempted to address the issue for DNA cases by creating a publicly available spreadsheet-based database called 'DNA-TrAC' 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DNA-TRAC2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It is a collection of summary information about published DNA TPPR articles to enable practitioners from around the world to be aware of existing literature on the topic.
 However,
 extracting data from the studies for use in downstream tools or systematic search for specific case circumstances are not available features.
 At the time of writing,
 the database contained information on 311 studies from 1993-2020.
 The ongoing maintenance of this database is reliant on voluntary community-led contribution,
 so the collection is limited,
 and future updates are not exhaustive and occur sporadically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More recently,
 a more extensive collection has been collected in Canada that included 3614 studies at the time of publication covering multiple trace types 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cadola_occurrence_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This database continues to be supported by students.
 Unfortunately,
 the contents of the listed publications are not included and require a querying practitioner to access the full text through publisher paywalls.
 A free open-source repository of curated TPPR data (rather than publication information) remains unrealised 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DNA-TRAC2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Address the learning curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dynamic nature of crime means that a comprehensive approach to forensic casework reporting needs to be embedded.
 Reporting of individual sample findings without the context of the entirety of case circumstances may mislead the significance of results when the background knowledge of the practitioner's expectations is not communicated.
 Standardisation of global investigation and reporting practices is required to ensure analysis is transparent and discipline specific knowledge is communicated clearly to guide understanding.
 For example,
 the use of the CAI model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cook1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in the investigation pathway would ensure that casework analysis takes a scientific approach of setting hypotheses (in the form of propositions) and then carrying out analyses to determine support for these rather than being findings-led or carrying out standard analysis processes regardless of case circumstances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A logical framework for activity-level evaluations has been characterised in the literature as they are akin to evaluations at a lower level of the hierarchy in using Bayesian methodology.
 Many practitioners feel that the learning curve for Bayesian Networks is too steep.
 Recognition that a Bayesian Network is the visualisation of an extended version of Bayes Theorem may aid in the acceptability of this as an evaluation tool.
 The outcome of a BN remains a likelihood ratio for reporting to the fact-finder and still requires the assumptions and caveats of Bayesian statistics commonly used at a sub-source level.
 For example,
 an assumption that the propositions that have been assessed are exhaustive within the framework of case circumstances and any other additional scenarios would require additional evaluation.
 Work that increases the usability of Bayesian Networks for the average forensic practitioner would also improve the perception of this tool.
 For example,
 the curation of centralised TPPR data repositories available to practitioners,
 using AI tools to support the generation of BNs using case circumstances and creating improved interrogation methods for models to determine the source of probability values that have been used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A notable difference to sub-source evaluations is that the issues that activity-level evaluations address are highly complex,
 often with incomplete data,
 and their case-specific nature requires a case-based approach 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "biedermann_importance_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 As such,
 there are additional considerations in which a practitioner needs to be trained prior to performing casework evaluations.
 A training standard must be documented,
 setting out the skill set,
 and depth of knowledge required to be able to conduct activity-level evaluations.
 Forensic service providers need to support the upskilling of their staff as the need for such assessments grows.
 The University of Lausanne course has been running several years and graduates are available to implement activity-level evaluations for case work and pass on their knowledge to their organisations through organisational training programs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The global implementation of activity-level evaluations requires not only the up-skilling of forensic practitioners but also acceptance by the legal community to be effective.
 This requires the setup of a training framework for judges and legal counsel to promote its acceptance in multiple legal jurisdictions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Implement what makes sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Time and cost restraints of a practicing forensic service provider may limit the implementation of activity-level evaluations,
 or which cases are considered for evaluation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tayloretal2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In addition,
 a paucity of data can restrict practitioners from providing an evaluation for certain cases.
 Still,
 these factors should not stop all assessments.
 If appropriately trained and competent staff are available and documented policies and procedures are implemented,
 there should be no barrier to the provision of activity-level evaluations in specific cases.
 There will be some cases where the circumstances are clear on the factors involved and published experiments are available to provide prior knowledge for the question at hand.
 If a clear,
 data-supported evaluation is conducted that is open to critique then the admissibility of the expert opinion should logically be no different to evaluations carried out at lower level in the proposition hierarchy.
 Instead of taking a stance that all activity-level proposition evaluation is not robust,
 it is advocated that each case be critically assessed to determine if there is sufficient understanding for trained practitioners to complete an evaluation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
An integrated approach to forensic science.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Forensic evaluative reporting is a cross-disciplinary concern.
 This means that guidelines and standards should advocate consistency across all disciplines.
 Additionally,
 there has been a recent rise of the idea of forensic intelligence,
 where a multi-case or whole-case/cross-discipline approach is taken to support resolution of casework and move towards a proactive approach to crime prevention 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "taylor_forensic_2024,oatley_forensic_2020,johnson_tracey_l_national_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 With the current position of a discipline-centric view of expertise and sample interpretation,
 crucial supporting information is not being included in evaluations.
 For example,
 a blood stain on a piece of broken glass containing DNA that matches a suspect would be made more informative if combined with the refractive index measurement from the fragment being consistent with a window from a crime scene.
 This idea was supported in a global survey of practitioners 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "airlie_contemporary_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Butler (2024) also points out that 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

multiple traces of the activity can be expected,
 and therefore in most cases it would be inadequate for report users or the court to consider only a single trace in isolation
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "butler_dna_2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Forensic analysts should use all task-relevant knowledge and technology available to them to provide support for justice outcomes.
 A mechanism to combine findings from different disciplines in activity-level evaluations has been suggested 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Koeijer2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is an extension of the summation rule of probability (P(C) = P(A) + P(B)) where determined likelihoods for disparate traces,
 regardless of forensic discipline,
 can be combined to give support to a single set of opposing propositions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Koeijer2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However,
 there needs to be shift in mindset for this to occur 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ross_forensic_2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 OSAC guidelines state that 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Task-relevant information does not include information such as prior convictions or allegations,
 and evidence from other forensic disciplines
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

...
 the presence of other evidence are examples of information that is not useful and potentially harmful
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "organization_of_scientific_area_committees_osac_for_forensic_science_best_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 ENFSI guidelines explicitly state that 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

Forensic practitioners will not report on matters outside their own area of expertise.
\begin_inset ERT
