"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Acknowledging that this is completely understandable for casework with current training practices and not all information from other disciplines would be helpful or relevant,
 change is needed to avoid holding back avenues of useful and relevant additive information.
 It suggests that future training for activity-level evaluations that includes evidence from different disciplines would need to cover the TPPR characteristics and processing methods relating to all forms of evidential traces.
 Quality Standards and care are needed if using a multi-case approach.
 Calculated likelihoods could be highly influenced by minor changes in case circumstances that might be missed if superficially similar cases are compared.
 To address this potential bias,
 it is necessary to consider all case differences during an evaluation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In parallel to the rise of forensic intelligence,
 a discussion has arisen on characterising the essence of forensic science 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "roux_forensic_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This amalgamated in the Sydney Declaration in 2022 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "roux_sydney_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The declaration set out a high-level understanding of what is means to be the field of forensic science.
 This is over and above the individual disciplines that are required for casework analysis.
 It set out seven holistic principles of forensic science that describe the nature and concerns of forensic practice 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "roux_sydney_2022"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Both the Sydney declaration and forensic intelligence are likely to influence many future conversations on the direction of forensic science.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Address the gaps in guidelines and set up accreditation systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although existing guidelines cover most issues in activity-level evaluation reporting,
 there are still some areas that need clarity.
 For example,
 understanding how it fits with the requirements of diverse legal systems and how an accreditation system would be structured.
 Setting of standards for training of both forensic practitioners and legal community is also still required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additionally,
 apart from the ENFSI,
 UKFR and ANZPAA-NIFS guidelines,
 all other guidance documents have focussed on forensic biology findings.
 The activity-level evaluations are a concern in all comparative disciplines and while many of the recommendations from the guidelines apply wider that forensic biology,
 domain-specific differences need to be assessed.
 Further thought also needs to occur to consider the integration of information across disciplines within a case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is still a need for extensive work to move towards globally accepted accreditation and quality assurance systems for activity-level evaluations,
 including standard operating procedures,
 proficiency testing regimes and technical review processes.
 This requires the input from key experts,
 specialist working groups,
 proficiency test providers and standards organisations.
 The communication of individual laboratory policies and practices where activity-level evaluations are conducted may guide other laboratories who are ready to start their own journey.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a risk that barriers to the reporting of activity-level evaluations will inhibit the ability of the future forensic practitioner to provide support to the judicial system.
 As more cases focus on the activity rather than sub-source attribution,
 forensic science starts to provide less probative value.
 While concerns are valid in some respects,
 holding back all activity-level evaluations is not viable as a long-term future.
 Allowing activity-level evaluations,
 when appropriate training,
 caveats and limitations are set in place,
 will grow the robustness of the science through use and familiarity.
 Additionally,
 ongoing discussion on the future direction and state of forensic science has given impetus to the attainment of global agreements.
 Overcoming the barriers that remain to activity-level evaluations should be prioritised.
\end_layout

